    "body": "@AskAlexSharov Thanks that worked!\r\n\r\nI'd say the most intuitive way is simply to keep the old behavior, and let the rpc daemon trying to connect to localhost:9090 TxPool Api if it can't find it at the time, without throwing any errors - Just print a warning to let the user know about it. Most likely that won't lead to confusion since the user has configured erigon with --txpool.disable, so he wouldn't expect to have a tx pool service for the daemon.\r\n\r\nIf this is not possible the things that felt most natural to do after getting that error for me were:\r\n- Removing --txpool.api.addr=localhost:9090 completely from the rpc daemon arguments (I read somewhere that this new argument is required with the new TxPool, so removing it would mean I don't want to connect there right?)\r\n- Adding --txpool.disable as an argument to rpc daemon as well, letting the daemon explicitly know that I don't want the TxPool and it should not even try to connect.",
